Although the exact date of establishment is unknown, it is伝えられている that in the past, fishermen from {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田}} and {{ill|Tsugaru|ja|津軽}} would travel here every spring for fishing and return in autumn. To escape dangers posed by the {{ill|Ainu|ja|アイヌ}}, they built a small shrine enshrining the {{ill|Osema|ja|大麻}} (talisman) from {{ill|Ise Jingū|ja|伊勢神宮}} in {{ill|Karatsunai Town|ja|唐津内町}}, calling it "Ise-dō." 

In the 10th year of {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era}} ({{ill|1582|ja|1582nd year }}), the feudal lord {{ill|Kaisaki Norihiro|ja|蛎崎（松前）季広}} relocated his seat to Kuramachi (present-day Fukuyama in Matsumae Town, 松前町字福山) and renamed the shrine as "Shinmei-sha" in reverence. In the first year of {{ill|Shōō|ja|承応}} the lord of the {{ill|Matsumae Domain|ja|松前藩}}, {{ill|Matsumae Takahiro|ja|松前高広}}, built a new shrine building at the present location, relocating the shrine and officially receiving the sacred seal ({{ill|Shinji|ja|神璽}}) from {{ill|Ise Jingū|ja|伊勢神宮}}. In the 4th year of {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治}} in November, it was ranked as a mura-sha, and in December of the 8th year of Meiji the shrine was renamed "Tokuyama Daijingu," and in the following year (the 9th year of Meiji) it was promoted to a gōsha. In February of the 4th year of {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正}} it was designated as a Shinzenheihaku-ryō Kōshin Shrine.

On March 5 of the 46th year of {{ill|Showa|ja|昭和}}, the main shrine building was designated as a tangible cultural property of Hokkaido, and it was repaired in the 52nd year of Showa; concurrently, the worship hall was rebuilt in the Shinmei style, with completion tier 1]][[Category: in the following year (the 53rd year of Showa).

== Sub-shrines ==
Within the shrine precincts is a subsidiary shrine: Haguro Shrine (【associated with】 {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶姫命}}).

== Cultural Properties ==
* Main shrine building (designated by Hokkaido)
