'''Tokuyama Daijingu''' (徳山大神宮) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Matsumae District|ja|松前郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Matsumae Town|ja|松前町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at Shinmei 66. Its enshrined deities are {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Toyouke Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which are the primary deities, although an additional 46 deities are also enshrined (as described below). The former shrine Ranking under the modern system was that of a Gōsha, and it is called the "Ichinomiya of Oshima" (渡島一宮).

== Worshipped deities (Saijin) ==
{{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}}
The primary enshrined deities are {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Toyouke Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and additionally 46 other deities are enshrined together (see below).

== History ==
Although the exact date of establishment is unknown, it is伝えられている that in the past, fishermen from {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Tsugaru|ja|津軽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would travel here every spring for fishing and return in autumn. To escape dangers posed by the {{ill|Ainu|ja|アイヌ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, they built a small shrine enshrining the {{ill|Osema|ja|大麻|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (talisman) from {{ill|Ise Jingū|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Karatsunai Town|ja|唐津内町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, calling it "Ise-dō." 

In the 10th year of {{ill|Tenshō|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|1582|ja|1582nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), the feudal lord {{ill|Kaisaki Norihiro|ja|蛎崎（松前）季広|qq=draft|qq=draft}} relocated his seat to Kuramachi (present-day Fukuyama in Matsumae Town, 松前町字福山) and renamed the shrine as "Shinmei-sha" in reverence. In the first year of {{ill|Shōō|ja|承応|qq=draft|qq=draft}} the lord of the {{ill|Matsumae Domain|ja|松前藩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Matsumae Takahiro|ja|松前高広|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, built a new shrine building at the present location, relocating the shrine and officially receiving the sacred seal ({{ill|Shinji|ja|神璽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) from {{ill|Ise Jingū|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In the 4th year of {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in November, it was Ranked as a mura-sha, and in December of the 8th year of Meiji the shrine was renamed "Tokuyama Daijingu," and in the following year (the 9th year of Meiji) it was promoted to a gōsha. In February of the 4th year of {{ill|Taishō|ja|大正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} it was designated as a Shinzenheihaku-ryō Kōshin Shrine.

On March 5 of the 46th year of {{ill|Showa|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the main shrine building was designated as a tangible cultural property of Hokkaido, and it was repaired in the 52nd year of Showa; concurrently, the worship hall was rebuilt in the Shinmei style, with Completion tier 1]][[Category: in the following year (the 53rd year of Showa).

== Sub-shrines ==
Within the shrine precincts is a subsidiary shrine: Haguro Shrine (【associated with】 {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花咲耶姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).

== Cultural Properties ==
* Main shrine building (designated by Hokkaido)
* Ridge plaque (designated by Hokkaido) (36 units)
* Torii (designated by Hokkaido)

