'''Tokuyama Daijingu''' (徳山大神宮) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Hokkaido|en|Hokkaido|WD=Q35581|lt=Hokkaido|1=Hokkaido}}, {{ill|Matsumae District, Hokkaido|en|Matsumae District, Hokkaido|WD=Q1145821|lt=Matsumae District|1=Matsumae District, Hokkaido}}, {{ill|Matsumae Town|ja|松前町|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsumae Town|1=松前町|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1307271}} at Shinmei 66. Its enshrined deities are {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu Ōmikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天照大神}} and {{ill|Toyouke Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Ōmikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to トヨウケビメ|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q2983724}}, which are the primary deities, although an additional 46 deities are also enshrined (as described below). The former shrine Ranking under the modern system was that of a Gōsha, and it is called the "Ichinomiya of Oshima" (渡島一宮).

== Worshipped deities (Saijin) ==
{{see also|{{ill|Saijin|ja|祭神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saijin|qq=}}}}
The primary enshrined deities are {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu Ōmikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天照大神}} and {{ill|Toyouke Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Ōmikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to トヨウケビメ|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q2983724}}, and additionally 46 other deities are enshrined together (see below).

== History ==
Although the exact date of establishment is unknown, it is伝えられている that in the past, fishermen from {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akita|1=Q11256953|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11256953}} and {{ill|Tsugaru|ja|津軽|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsugaru|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 津軽地方|1=Tsugaru region|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11556401}} would travel here every spring for fishing and return in autumn. To escape dangers posed by the {{ill|Ainu people|en|Ainu people|WD=Q101828|lt=Ainu|1=Ainu people}}, they built a small shrine enshrining the {{ill|Cannabis (drug)|en|Cannabis (drug)|WD=Q2845|lt=Osema|1=Cannabis (drug)}} (talisman) from {{ill|Ise Shrine|en|Ise Shrine|WD=Q687168|lt=Ise Jingū|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} in {{ill|Karatsunai Town|ja|唐津内町|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karatsunai Town|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, calling it "Ise-dō." 

In the 10th year of {{ill|Tenshō (Momoyama period)|en|Tenshō (Momoyama period)|WD=Q1145058|lt=Tenshō Era|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} ({{ill|1582|en|1582|WD=Q6719|lt=1582|1=1582}}), the feudal lord {{ill|Kaisaki Norihiro|ja|蛎崎（松前）季広|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaisaki Norihiro|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} relocated his seat to Kuramachi (present-day Fukuyama in Matsumae Town, 松前町字福山) and renamed the shrine as "Shinmei-sha" in reverence. In the first year of {{ill|Jōō (Edo period)|en|Jōō (Edo period)|WD=Q1145081|lt=Shōō|1=Jōō (Edo period)}} the lord of the {{ill|Matsumae Domain|en|Matsumae Domain|WD=Q18669712|lt=Matsumae Domain|1=Matsumae Domain}}, {{ill|Matsumae Takahiro|ja|松前高広|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsumae Takahiro|1=Matsumae Takahiro|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q8514302}}, built a new shrine building at the present location, relocating the shrine and officially receiving the sacred seal ({{ill|Shinji|ja|神璽|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinji|1=Shenxi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q5371535}}) from {{ill|Ise Shrine|en|Ise Shrine|WD=Q687168|lt=Ise Jingū|1=Ise Grand Shrine}}. In the 4th year of {{ill|Meiji era|en|Meiji era|WD=Q3125096|lt=Meiji era|1=Meiji era}} in November, it was Ranked as a mura-sha, and in December of the 8th year of Meiji the shrine was renamed "Tokuyama Daijingu," and in the following year (the 9th year of Meiji) it was promoted to a gōsha. In February of the 4th year of {{ill|Taishō era|en|Taishō era|WD=Q329174|lt=Taishō|1=Taishō era}} it was designated as a Shinzenheihaku-ryō Kōshin Shrine.

On March 5 of the 46th year of {{ill|Shōwa era|en|Shōwa era|WD=Q327567|lt=Showa|1=Shōwa era}}, the main shrine building was designated as a tangible cultural property of Hokkaido, and it was repaired in the 52nd year of Showa; concurrently, the worship hall was rebuilt in the Shinmei style, with Completion tier 1]])
